lly, the nginx docs mention a <code>http</code> directive which is unnecessary for us, as it is already included by the configuration in the container. Our nginx configuration now looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>upstream wpcluster {\n        server wordpress1;\n        server wordpress2;\n        server wordpress3;\n}\n\nserver {\n        listen 80 default_server;\n        listen   &#91;::]:80 default_server;\n\n        server_name example.com;\n        location / {\n            proxy_pass http://wpcluster;\n\n        }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->','Part 3: Using nginx as a load balancer','','inherit','closed','closed','','28-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 16:42:00','2023-02-24 16:42:00','',28,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=37',0,'revision','',0),(39,2,'2023-02-24 16:47:39','2023-02-24 16:47:39','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The next part of our journey will involve creating a load balancer configuration in nginx, and using it to spread the incoming load to our WordPress site across three identical WordPress instances serving the same content. To do this, we create an <code>upstream</code> cluster in our nginx configuration file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, we will modify <code>docker-compose.yml</code> to start three WordPress containers, <code>wordpress1</code>,  <code>wordpress2</code>, and (you guessed it) <code>wordpress3</code>. These containers will have identical settings - in particular, all three will share the same volume for the WordPress distribution files - this guarantees that all three will have the same settings and plug-in setup. Our <code>docker-compose.yml</code> now looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>version: \"3\"\n\nservices:\n  proxy:\n    <em>unchanged</em>\n\n  wordpress1:\n    restart: always\n    image: wordpress:6.1-apache\n    depends_on:\n      db:\n        condition: service_healthy\n    environment:\n      WORDPRESS_DB_HOST: \'db\'\n      WORDPRESS_DB_USER: \'wordpress\'\n      WORDPRESS_DB_PASSWORD: \'password1234\'\n      WORDPRESS_DB_NAME: \'wordpress\'\n    networks:\n      - external_network\n    volumes:\n      - ./wordpress:/var/www/html\n\n  wordpress2:\n    <em>exact copy of wordpress1</em>\n\n  wordpress3:\n    <em>exact copy of wordpress1</em>\n\n  db:\n    <em>unchanged</em>\nnetworks:\n  external_network:</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And in <code>nginx/conf.d/wordpress.conf</code> we now use an <code>upstream</code> group to define the services we will load balance across. The default load balancing method is round-robin (1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3, ...), but there are <a href=\"https://docs.nginx.com/nginx/admin-guide/load-balancer/http-load-balancer/\">many options documented in the nginx docs</a>. Among these: we can send requests to the node that has the least active connections, or to a random node in the cluster. For session-aware applications, we can always send requests from the same client to the same server. We can also weight certain containers more or less (enabling, for example, A-B testing using the load balancer). Incidentally, the nginx docs mention a <code>http</code> directive which is unnecessary for us, as it is already included by the configuration in the container. Our nginx configuration now looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>upstream wpcluster {\n        server wordpress1;\n        server wordpress2;\n        server wordpress3;\n}\n\nserver {\n        listen 80 default_server;\n        listen   &#91;::]:80 default_server;\n\n        server_name example.com;\n        location / {\n            proxy_pass http://wpcluster;\n\n        }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This time, when we start our service in <code>wordpress3</code>, we see five containers starting. No container images are downloaded, since we are just starting three copies of the same image for WordPress.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;opc@cloud-native-wordpress wordpress3]$ docker-compose up -d\n&#91;+] Running 6/6\n  Network wordpress3_external_network  Created                                                                  0.2s\n  Container wordpress3-proxy-1         Started                                                                  0.6s\n  Container wordpress3-db-1            Healthy                                                                 21.1s\n  Container wordpress3-wordpress3-1    Started                                                                 21.6s\n  Container wordpress3-wordpress1-1    Started                                                                 21.5s\n  Container wordpress3-wordpress2-1    Started                                                                 21.7s</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you run <code>docker-compose logs -f</code> now, you will see requests for resources are being directed to all three WordPress nodes by the proxy service.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 3: Using nginx as a load balancer','','inherit','closed','closed','','28-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 16:47:39','2023-02-24 16:47:39','',28,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=39',0,'revision','',0),(40,2,'2023-02-24 16:48:23','2023-02-24 16:48:23','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The next part of our journey will involve creating a load balancer configuration in nginx, and using it to spread the incoming load to our WordPress site across three identical WordPress instances serving the same content. To do this, we create an <code>upstream</code> cluster in our nginx configuration file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, we will modify <code>docker-compose.yml</code> to start three WordPress containers, <code>wordpress1</code>,  <code>wordpress2</code>, and (you guessed it) <code>wordpress3</code>. These containers will have identical settings - in particular, all three will share the same volume for the WordPress distribution files - this guarantees that all three will have the same settings and plug-in setup. Our <code>docker-compose.yml</code> now looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>version: \"3\"\n\nservices:\n  proxy:\n    <em>unchanged</em>\n\n  wordpress1:\n    restart: always\n    image: wordpress:6.1-apache\n    depends_on:\n      db:\n        condition: service_healthy\n    environment:\n      WORDPRESS_DB_HOST: \'db\'\n      WORDPRESS_DB_USER: \'wordpress\'\n      WORDPRESS_DB_PASSWORD: \'password1234\'\n      WORDPRESS_DB_NAME: \'wordpress\'\n    networks:\n      - external_network\n    volumes:\n      - ./wordpress:/var/www/html\n\n  wordpress2:\n    <em>exact copy of wordpress1</em>\n\n  wordpress3:\n    <em>exact copy of wordpress1</em>\n\n  db:\n    <em>unchanged</em>\nnetworks:\n  external_network:</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And in <code>nginx/conf.d/wordpress.conf</code> we now use an <code>upstream</code> group to define the services we will load balance across. The default load balancing method is round-robin (1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3, ...), but there are <a href=\"https://docs.nginx.com/nginx/admin-guide/load-balancer/http-load-balancer/\">many options documented in the nginx docs</a>. Among these: we can send requests to the node that has the least active connections, or to a random node in the cluster. For session-aware applications, we can always send requests from the same client to the same server. We can also weight certain containers more or less (enabling, for example, A-B testing using the load balancer). Incidentally, the nginx docs mention a <code>http</code> directive which is unnecessary for us, as it is already included by the configuration in the container. Our nginx configuration now looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>upstream wpcluster {\n        server wordpress1;\n        server wordpress2;\n        server wordpress3;\n}\n\nserver {\n        listen 80 default_server;\n        listen   &#91;::]:80 default_server;\n\n        server_name example.com;\n        location / {\n            proxy_pass http://wpcluster;\n\n        }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This time, when we start our service in <code>wordpress3</code>, we see five containers starting. No container images are downloaded, since we are just starting three copies of the same image for WordPress.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;opc@cloud-native-wordpress wordpress3]$ docker-compose up -d\n&#91;+] Running 6/6\n  Network wordpress3_external_network  Created                                                                  0.2s\n  Container wordpress3-proxy-1         Started                                                                  0.6s\n  Container wordpress3-db-1            Healthy                                                                 21.1s\n  Container wordpress3-wordpress3-1    Started                                                                 21.6s\n  Container wordpress3-wordpress1-1    Started                                                                 21.5s\n  Container wordpress3-wordpress2-1    Started                                                                 21.7s</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you run <code>docker-compose logs -f</code> now, you will see requests for resources are being directed to all three WordPress nodes by the proxy service. As all three share the same volume for WordPress files, and connect to the same back-end database, from the user\'s perspective, they are identical.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 3: Using nginx as a load balancer','','inherit','closed','closed','','28-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 16:48:23','2023-02-24 16:48:23','',28,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=40',0,'revision','',0),(42,2,'2023-02-24 16:54:35','2023-02-24 16:54:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now we will enable ourselves to evolve the application architecture by separating out the HTTP end-point that users connect to from the application server that is serving content. To do this, we will use <code>nginx</code> as a fast, lightweight proxy, and continue to use an Apache2/php instance running WordPress to generate the dynamic content. For the moment, wer should not see a big change in performance, but this is an important step to enabling us to scale our application by caching content, and load-balancing compute-heavy work across multiple instances.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The main change we will make in <code>docker-compose.yml</code> is to add a new <code>proxy</code> service which will download the latest <code>nginx</code> container, pass through host port 80 to the container (we remove this config from our <code>wordpress</code> container) and map a custom configuration for our WordPress install into the <code>/etc/nginx/conf.d</code> directory of our container. This basic nginx configuration specifies that we are the default server for all connections to port 80, regardless of the requested domain name (this allows us to connect using just the IP address), and that all requests should be passed to the <code>wordpress</code> service:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>server {\n        listen 80 default_server;\n        listen   &#91;::]:80 default_server;\n\n        server_name example.com;\n        location / {\n            proxy_pass http://wordpress;\n        }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We also added a new database file to <code>mysql/initdb</code> which maps to the special directory in the container <code>/docker-entrypoint-initdb.d</code> - if the database is not already initialized, the database back-up in this directory will automatically be loaded at start-up, as described in <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/mysql\">the DockerHub page for MySQL</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we start the application with a database dump, it takes a few seconds for the database to become available. We can force the <code>wordpress</code> container to wait for the database to be ready by adding a <code>depends_on</code> condition to the WordPress container options.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before starting our application, you will need to update two IP addresses used by WordPress as part of its configuration. In <code>mysql/initdb/pi_day.sql</code>, search for the IP address <code>129.213.187.155</code> (the IP address obtained by me while preparing this tutorial) and replace it with the IP address for your instance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After running <code>docker-compose up -d</code> with this file, we now have 3 containers running, and the service should take about 20 seconds to start up, because WordPress now waits for the database to become available after loading our saved database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;opc@cloud-native-wordpress wordpress2]$ docker-compose up -d\n&#91;+] Running 4/4\n  Network wordpress2_external_network  Created                                                                  0.3s\n  Container wordpress2-db-1            Healthy                                                                 21.0s\n  Container wordpress2-proxy-1         Started                                                                  0.6s\n  Container wordpress2-wordpress-1     Started                                                                 21.3s\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now see how queries are being handled by the server by checking the logs with <code>docker-compose logs -f</code> (the <code>-f</code> option allows us to follow along in real-time) while we interact with the website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we send a request to the site, we first see that the message is intercepted by <code>wordpress2-proxy-1</code> before being passed along to <code>wordpress2-wordpress-1</code>, where the page request is satisfied and returned to the requester.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>wordpress2-wordpress-1  | 172.20.0.4 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:01 +0000] \"GET / HTTP/1.0\" 200 11352 \"-\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\"\nwordpress2-proxy-1      | 173.76.40.122 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:01 +0000] \"GET / HTTP/1.1\" 200 10949 \"-\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\" \"-\"\nwordpress2-proxy-1      | 173.76.40.122 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:02 +0000] \"GET /2023/02/24/welcome-to-pi-day-2023/ HTTP/1.1\" 200 14761 \"http://129.213.187.155/\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\" \"-\"\nwordpress2-wordpress-1  | 172.20.0.4 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:02 +0000] \"GET /2023/02/24/welcome-to-pi-day-2023/ HTTP/1.0\" 200 15359 \"http://129.213.187.155/\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\"</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before proceeding: a word on creating database back-ups. To run commands in the context of the container, we can use <code>docker-compose exec servicename &lt;cmd></code>. To generate database back-ups for our WordPress instance, we run <code>mysqldump</code> inside the container as the database root user - giving the database root password we passed to the container at startup when prompter - and save the SQL file generated to the local filesystem, with:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>docker-compose exec db mysqldump -u root -p wordpress > pi_day.sql</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When running a live service, you will want to do this every day in a cron job, and save several days of back-ups, to ensure that you can restore the service quickly in the event of unexpected data loss.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that we have a proxy, and the ability to reload our database after completely changing the application architecture, we are ready to experiment with load balancing! <a href=\"http://129.213.187.155/2023/02/24/using-nginx-as-a-load-balancer/\" data-type=\"post\" data-id=\"28\">Let\'s move on to part 3</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 2: Adding a proxy','','inherit','closed','closed','','13-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 16:54:35','2023-02-24 16:54:35','',13,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=42',0,'revision','',0),(44,2,'2023-02-24 16:58:15','2023-02-24 16:58:15','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The next part of our journey will involve creating a load balancer configuration in nginx, and using it to spread the incoming load to our WordPress site across three identical WordPress instances serving the same content. To do this, we create an <code>upstream</code> cluster in our nginx configuration file. For this phase of the project, we will use the files in <code>wordpress3</code> in our repository.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, we will modify <code>docker-compose.yml</code> to start three WordPress containers, <code>wordpress1</code>,  <code>wordpress2</code>, and (you guessed it) <code>wordpress3</code>. These containers will have identical settings - in particular, all three will share the same volume for the WordPress distribution files - this guarantees that all three will have the same settings and plug-in setup. Our <code>docker-compose.yml</code> now looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>version: \"3\"\n\nservices:\n  proxy:\n    <em>unchanged</em>\n\n  wordpress1:\n    restart: always\n    image: wordpress:6.1-apache\n    depends_on:\n      db:\n        condition: service_healthy\n    environment:\n      WORDPRESS_DB_HOST: \'db\'\n      WORDPRESS_DB_USER: \'wordpress\'\n      WORDPRESS_DB_PASSWORD: \'password1234\'\n      WORDPRESS_DB_NAME: \'wordpress\'\n    networks:\n      - external_network\n    volumes:\n      - ./wordpress:/var/www/html\n\n  wordpress2:\n    <em>exact copy of wordpress1</em>\n\n  wordpress3:\n    <em>exact copy of wordpress1</em>\n\n  db:\n    <em>unchanged</em>\nnetworks:\n  external_network:</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And in <code>nginx/conf.d/wordpress.conf</code> we now use an <code>upstream</code> group to define the services we will load balance across. The default load balancing method is round-robin (1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3, ...), but there are <a href=\"https://docs.nginx.com/nginx/admin-guide/load-balancer/http-load-balancer/\">many options documented in the nginx docs</a>. Among these: we can send requests to the node that has the least active connections, or to a random node in the cluster. For session-aware applications, we can always send requests from the same client to the same server. We can also weight certain containers more or less (enabling, for example, A-B testing using the load balancer). Incidentally, the nginx docs mention a <code>http</code> directive which is unnecessary for us, as it is already included by the configuration in the container. Our nginx configuration now looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>upstream wpcluster {\n        server wordpress1;\n        server wordpress2;\n        server wordpress3;\n}\n\nserver {\n        listen 80 default_server;\n        listen   &#91;::]:80 default_server;\n\n        server_name example.com;\n        location / {\n            proxy_pass http://wpcluster;\n\n        }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This time, when we start our service in <code>wordpress3</code>, we see five containers starting. No container images are downloaded, since we are just starting three copies of the same image for WordPress.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;opc@cloud-native-wordpress wordpress3]$ docker-compose up -d\n&#91;+] Running 6/6\n  Network wordpress3_external_network  Created                                                                  0.2s\n  Container wordpress3-proxy-1         Started                                                                  0.6s\n  Container wordpress3-db-1            Healthy                                                                 21.1s\n  Container wordpress3-wordpress3-1    Started                                                                 21.6s\n  Container wordpress3-wordpress1-1    Started                                                                 21.5s\n  Container wordpress3-wordpress2-1    Started                                                                 21.7s</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you run <code>docker-compose logs -f</code> now, you will see requests for resources are being directed to all three WordPress nodes by the proxy service. As all three share the same volume for WordPress files, and connect to the same back-end database, from the user\'s perspective, they are identical.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that we have our service load balancing, we should figure out how to do less work, not more. That means enabling some caching. In our next step, we will add a Redis object cache for WordPress, add a caching plug-in to WordPress to provide page caching, and use nginx as a reverse-proxy cache for static resources.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 3: Using nginx as a load balancer','','inherit','closed','closed','','28-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 16:58:15','2023-02-24 16:58:15','',28,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=44',0,'revision','',0),(45,2,'2023-02-24 17:06:38','2023-02-24 17:06:38','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. First, we will add a new <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/redis\">Redis service</a> to our Docker application in <code>docker-compose.yml</code>. The default container configuration will suffice for us, since our Redis instance will not be exposed outside of our container application:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>services:\n<em>Unchanged until after the db service</em>\n  redis:\n    image: redis:latest\n    restart: always\n    networks:\n      - external_network</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now when we next run <code>docker-compose up -d</code> we will see the Redis image and underlying layers being pulled and the container started.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our next stop is to install a WordPress caching plug-in. In the WordPress admin view, visit the \"Plugins\" page, and select \"Add new\". We are going to install two plugins - one to cache WordPress content for unauthenticated users, and another to enable us to connect to a Redis container.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":64,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Add_Redis_plugin-1024x558.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-64\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Searching for the Redis plugin</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, we will search for Redis and install and activate the official <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/redis-cache/\">Redis Object Cache</a> plugin. To enable our WordPress instance to connect to our Redis instance, we will also need to add two options manually to the end of our WordPress configuration file <code>wordpress/wp-config.php</code>, before the line saying \"That\'s all, stop editing!\" Because the user in the WordPress container does not match the <code>opc</code> userid, we will edit the file as root using <code>sudo</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>...\n// Redis configuration\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_HOST\', \'redis\');\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_PORT\', \'6379\');\n\n/* That\'s all, stop editing! Happy publishing. */\n...</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the Redis plugin options, we can now verify that the object cache is working by enabling the object cache, the connection will be verified. Our Redis instance will now be used automatically as an object cache by WordPress. This means that when PHP objects are created in memory for things like users, posts, and pages, those objects will be stored in Redis in addition to being used to generate web pages for the user. The next time the same query is received, those objects will be loaded from Redis, rather than being created dynamically from a database query. As a result, we reduce both the load to the database, and the amount of PHP which needs to run to construct a page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":63,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Redis_object_cache_working.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-63\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The connection is validated</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we will install and activate <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-super-cache/\">WP Super Cache</a>, a page caching plugin. This plug-in will cache pages after they are created, and serve them to unauthenticated users. The installation is a two-step process. First we search for and install the plugin in the plugins page, then we need to activate the plugin in its settings page. After enabling page caching, we can test the caching on the settings page to verify that it is working.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":68,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/activated_wp_supercache-1024x536.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-68\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The WP SuperCache settings page after the plugin is activated</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The plug-in will provide a number of other useful resources for improving the performance of your page, but those are outside the scope of this tutorial.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We now have a multi-container application load-balancing calls across three WordPress instances, caching pages that can be served statically to improve performance, and caching PHP objects to reduce load on both our web servers and our database, all masked behind a proxy nginx service. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As I wrote at the beginning, there are many more steps possible to create a production service:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Enable secure HTTPS connections by generating and using SSL certificates</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Regularly backing up our database, and verifying emergency restoration</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Creating a custom container image with our plugins pre-installed to make automated deployment and upgrades easier</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Introducing monitoring to measure performance and receive alerts when the performance drops</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Moving to Kubernetes for a distributed, clustered application that can take advantage of cloud resources</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Using an object store for static resources added to the WordPress instance like uploaded images</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Concealing passwords with Kubernetes secrets</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Scaling our database, if that becomes necessary, with read-only replicas or sharding</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But already in a very short time, we can now connect multiple Docker containers together, scale our application using load balancing, and accelerate the performance for end-users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','publish','open','open','','enabling-caching','','','2023-02-28 20:01:18','2023-02-28 20:01:18','',0,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=45',0,'post','',0),(46,2,'2023-02-24 17:06:38','2023-02-24 17:06:38','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable easily for our WordPress installation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 17:06:38','2023-02-24 17:06:38','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=46',0,'revision','',0),(47,2,'2023-02-24 17:06:58','2023-02-24 17:06:58','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable easily for our WordPress installation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Step 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 17:06:58','2023-02-24 17:06:58','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=47',0,'revision','',0),(49,2,'2023-02-24 17:11:37','2023-02-24 17:11:37','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now we will enable ourselves to evolve the application architecture by separating out the HTTP end-point that users connect to from the application server that is serving content. To do this, we will use <code>nginx</code> as a fast, lightweight proxy, and continue to use an Apache2/php instance running WordPress to generate the dynamic content. For the moment, wer should not see a big change in performance, but this is an important step to enabling us to scale our application by caching content, and load-balancing compute-heavy work across multiple instances.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The main change we will make in <code>docker-compose.yml</code> is to add a new <code>proxy</code> service which will download the latest <code>nginx</code> container, pass through host port 80 to the container (we remove this config from our <code>wordpress</code> container).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>version: \"3\"\n\nservices:\n  proxy:\n    restart: always\n    image: nginx:latest\n    networks: \n      - external_network\n    ports:\n      - 80:80\n    volumes:\n      - ./nginx/tmp:/var/run/nginx\n      - ./nginx/conf.d:/etc/nginx/conf.d\n    command: &#91; nginx-debug, \'-g\', \'daemon off;\' ]\n<em>everything else is unchanged</em></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We now map a custom configuration for our WordPress install into the <code>/etc/nginx/conf.d</code> directory of our container. This basic nginx configuration specifies that we are the default server for all connections to port 80, regardless of the requested domain name (this allows us to connect using just the IP address), and that all requests should be passed to the <code>wordpress</code> service:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>server {\n        listen 80 default_server;\n        listen   &#91;::]:80 default_server;\n\n        server_name example.com;\n        location / {\n            proxy_pass http://wordpress;\n        }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We also added a new database file to <code>mysql/initdb</code> which maps to the special directory in the container <code>/docker-entrypoint-initdb.d</code> - if the database is not already initialized, the database back-up in this directory will automatically be loaded at start-up, as described in <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/mysql\">the DockerHub page for MySQL</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we start the application with a database dump, it takes a few seconds for the database to become available. We can force the <code>wordpress</code> container to wait for the database to be ready by adding a <code>depends_on</code> condition to the WordPress container options.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before starting our application, you will need to update two IP addresses used by WordPress as part of its configuration. In <code>mysql/initdb/pi_day.sql</code>, search for the IP address <code>129.213.187.155</code> (the IP address obtained by me while preparing this tutorial) and replace it with the IP address for your instance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After running <code>docker-compose up -d</code> with this file, we now have 3 containers running, and the service should take about 20 seconds to start up, because WordPress now waits for the database to become available after loading our saved database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;opc@cloud-native-wordpress wordpress2]$ docker-compose up -d\n&#91;+] Running 4/4\n  Network wordpress2_external_network  Created                                                                  0.3s\n  Container wordpress2-db-1            Healthy                                                                 21.0s\n  Container wordpress2-proxy-1         Started                                                                  0.6s\n  Container wordpress2-wordpress-1     Started                                                                 21.3s\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now see how queries are being handled by the server by checking the logs with <code>docker-compose logs -f</code> (the <code>-f</code> option allows us to follow along in real-time) while we interact with the website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we send a request to the site, we first see that the message is intercepted by <code>wordpress2-proxy-1</code> before being passed along to <code>wordpress2-wordpress-1</code>, where the page request is satisfied and returned to the requester.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>wordpress2-wordpress-1  | 172.20.0.4 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:01 +0000] \"GET / HTTP/1.0\" 200 11352 \"-\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\"\nwordpress2-proxy-1      | 173.76.40.122 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:01 +0000] \"GET / HTTP/1.1\" 200 10949 \"-\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\" \"-\"\nwordpress2-proxy-1      | 173.76.40.122 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:02 +0000] \"GET /2023/02/24/welcome-to-pi-day-2023/ HTTP/1.1\" 200 14761 \"http://129.213.187.155/\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\" \"-\"\nwordpress2-wordpress-1  | 172.20.0.4 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:02 +0000] \"GET /2023/02/24/welcome-to-pi-day-2023/ HTTP/1.0\" 200 15359 \"http://129.213.187.155/\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\"</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before proceeding: a word on creating database back-ups. To run commands in the context of the container, we can use <code>docker-compose exec servicename &lt;cmd&gt;</code>. To generate database back-ups for our WordPress instance, we run <code>mysqldump</code> inside the container as the database root user - giving the database root password we passed to the container at startup when prompter - and save the SQL file generated to the local filesystem, with:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>docker-compose exec db mysqldump -u root -p wordpress &gt; pi_day.sql</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When running a live service, you will want to do this every day in a cron job, and save several days of back-ups, to ensure that you can restore the service quickly in the event of unexpected data loss.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that we have a proxy, and the ability to reload our database after completely changing the application architecture, we are ready to experiment with load balancing! <a href=\"http://129.213.187.155/2023/02/24/using-nginx-as-a-load-balancer/\" data-type=\"post\" data-id=\"28\">Let\'s move on to part 3</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 2: Adding a proxy','','inherit','closed','closed','','13-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 17:11:37','2023-02-24 17:11:37','',13,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=49',0,'revision','',0),(51,2,'2023-02-24 17:49:13','2023-02-24 17:49:13','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. Our first stop is nginx, which can be configured to be a reverse-proxy cache very easily. In <code>nginx/conf.d/wordpress.conf</code>, we add a <code>proxy_cache_path</code> directive with a path in the container, a name for the cache (we use <code>wordpress</code>), and a maximum size for the cache. Then inside our <code>server</code> block, we use this cache, and add a HTTP header <code>X-Cache</code> to enable debugging of our cache - this header will be set to <code>HIT</code> or <code>MISS</code>, depending on whether the requested resource was cached. We with also use a volume for the cache directory, which we specify in <code>docker-compose.yml</code>, to ensure that the directory exists in the container. Our <code>nginx/conf.d/wordpress.conf</code> file now looks like this: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>upstream wpcluster {\n	server wordpress1;\n	server wordpress2;\n	server wordpress3;\n}\n\nproxy_cache_path /data/nginx/cache keys_zone=wordpress:10m; \n\nserver {\n	proxy_cache wordpress;\n	add_header X-Cached $upstream_cache_status;\n\n        listen 80 default_server;\n        listen   &#91;::]:80 default_server;\n\n        server_name example.com;\n        location / {\n            proxy_pass http://wpcluster;\n\n        }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>and the <code>volumes</code>array in the configuration of the nginx service is now:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>    volumes:\n      - ./nginx/tmp:/var/run/nginx\n      - ./nginx/cache:/data/nginx/cache\n      - ./nginx/conf.d:/etc/nginx/conf.d</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->','Step 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 17:49:13','2023-02-24 17:49:13','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=51',0,'revision','',0),(52,2,'2023-02-24 17:49:22','2023-02-24 17:49:22','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. Our first stop is nginx, which can be configured to be a reverse-proxy cache very easily. In <code>nginx/conf.d/wordpress.conf</code>, we add a <code>proxy_cache_path</code> directive with a path in the container, a name for the cache (we use <code>wordpress</code>), and a maximum size for the cache. Then inside our <code>server</code> block, we use this cache, and add a HTTP header <code>X-Cache</code> to enable debugging of our cache - this header will be set to <code>HIT</code> or <code>MISS</code>, depending on whether the requested resource was cached. We with also use a volume for the cache directory, which we specify in <code>docker-compose.yml</code>, to ensure that the directory exists in the container. Our <code>nginx/conf.d/wordpress.conf</code> file now looks like this: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>upstream wpcluster {\n	server wordpress1;\n	server wordpress2;\n	server wordpress3;\n}\n\nproxy_cache_path /data/nginx/cache keys_zone=wordpress:10m; \n\nserver {\n	proxy_cache wordpress;\n	add_header X-Cached $upstream_cache_status;\n\n        listen 80 default_server;\n        listen   &#91;::]:80 default_server;\n\n        server_name example.com;\n        location / {\n            proxy_pass http://wpcluster;\n\n        }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>and the <code>volumes</code> array in the configuration of the nginx service is now:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>    volumes:\n      - ./nginx/tmp:/var/run/nginx\n      - ./nginx/cache:/data/nginx/cache\n      - ./nginx/conf.d:/etc/nginx/conf.d</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->','Step 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 17:49:22','2023-02-24 17:49:22','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=52',0,'revision','',0),(53,2,'2023-02-24 17:49:41','2023-02-24 17:49:41','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. Our first stop is nginx, which can be configured to be a reverse-proxy cache very easily. In <code>nginx/conf.d/wordpress.conf</code>, we add a <code>proxy_cache_path</code> directive with a path in the container, a name for the cache (we use <code>wordpress</code>), and a maximum size for the cache. Then inside our <code>server</code> block, we use this cache, and add a HTTP header <code>X-Cache</code> to enable debugging of our cache - this header will be set to <code>HIT</code> or <code>MISS</code>, depending on whether the requested resource was cached. We with also use a volume for the cache directory, which we specify in <code>docker-compose.yml</code>, to ensure that the directory exists in the container. Our <code>nginx/conf.d/wordpress.conf</code> file now looks like this: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>upstream wpcluster {\n	server wordpress1;\n	server wordpress2;\n	server wordpress3;\n}\n\nproxy_cache_path /data/nginx/cache keys_zone=wordpress:10m; \n\nserver {\n	proxy_cache wordpress;\n	add_header X-Cached $upstream_cache_status;\n\n        listen 80 default_server;\n        listen   &#91;::]:80 default_server;\n\n        server_name example.com;\n        location / {\n            proxy_pass http://wpcluster;\n\n        }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>and the <code>volumes</code> array in the configuration of the nginx service is now:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>    volumes:\n      - ./nginx/tmp:/var/run/nginx\n      - ./nginx/cache:/data/nginx/cache\n      - ./nginx/conf.d:/etc/nginx/conf.d</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 17:49:41','2023-02-24 17:49:41','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=53',0,'revision','',0),(55,2,'2023-02-24 18:43:10','2023-02-24 18:43:10','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. Our first stop is to install a WordPress caching plug-in</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 18:43:10','2023-02-24 18:43:10','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=55',0,'revision','',0),(56,2,'2023-02-24 18:45:27','2023-02-24 18:45:27','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. Our first stop is to install a WordPress caching plug-in. In the WordPress admin view, </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 18:45:27','2023-02-24 18:45:27','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=56',0,'revision','',0),(57,2,'2023-02-24 18:47:53','2023-02-24 18:47:53','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. Our first stop is to install a WordPress caching plug-in. In the WordPress admin view, visit the \"Plugins\" page, and select </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 18:47:53','2023-02-24 18:47:53','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=57',0,'revision','',0),(59,2,'2023-02-24 18:57:26','2023-02-24 18:57:26','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. First, we will add a new <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/redis\">Redis service</a> to our Docker application in <code>docker-compose.yml</code>. The default container configuration will suffice for us, since our Redis instance will not be exposed outside of our container application:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>services:\n<em>Unchanged until after the db service</em>\n  redis:\n    image: redis:latest\n    restart: always\n    networks:\n      - external_network</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now when we next run <code>docker-compose up -d</code> we will see the Redis image and underlying layers being pulled and the container started.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our next stop is to install a WordPress caching plug-in. In the WordPress admin view, visit the \"Plugins\" page, and select \"Add new\". We are going to install two plugins - one to cache WordPress content for unauthenticated users, and another to enable us to connect to a Redis container</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 18:57:26','2023-02-24 18:57:26','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=59',0,'revision','',0),(60,2,'2023-02-24 19:44:46','2023-02-24 19:44:46','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. First, we will add a new <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/redis\">Redis service</a> to our Docker application in <code>docker-compose.yml</code>. The default container configuration will suffice for us, since our Redis instance will not be exposed outside of our container application:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>services:\n<em>Unchanged until after the db service</em>\n  redis:\n    image: redis:latest\n    restart: always\n    networks:\n      - external_network</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now when we next run <code>docker-compose up -d</code> we will see the Redis image and underlying layers being pulled and the container started.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our next stop is to install a WordPress caching plug-in. In the WordPress admin view, visit the \"Plugins\" page, and select \"Add new\". We are going to install two plugins - one to cache WordPress content for unauthenticated users, and another to enable us to connect to a Redis container.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, we will search for Redis and install and activate the official <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/redis-cache/\">Redis Object Cache</a> plugin. To enable our WordPress instance to connect to our Redis instance, we will also need to add two options manually to the end of our WordPress configuration file <code>wordpress/wp-config.php</code>, before the line saying \"That\'s all, stop editing!\" Because the user in the WordPress container does not match the <code>opc</code> userid, we will edit the file as root using <code>sudo</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>...\n// Redis configuration\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_HOST\', \'redis\');\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_PORT\', \'6379\');\n\n/* That\'s all, stop editing! Happy publishing. */\n...</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our Redis instance will now be used automatically as an object cache by WordPress. This means that when PHP objects are created in memory for things like users, posts, and pages, those objects will be stored in Redis in addition to being used to generate web pages for the user. The next time the same query is received, those objects will be loaded from Redis, rather than being created dynamically from a database query. As a result, we reduce both the load to the database, and the amount of PHP which needs to run to construct a page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we will install and activate the plugin <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/w3-total-cache/\">W3 Total Cache</a>, a page caching plugin. This plug-in will cache </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 19:44:46','2023-02-24 19:44:46','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=60',0,'revision','',0),(61,2,'2023-02-24 19:45:13','2023-02-24 19:45:13','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. First, we will add a new <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/redis\">Redis service</a> to our Docker application in <code>docker-compose.yml</code>. The default container configuration will suffice for us, since our Redis instance will not be exposed outside of our container application:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>services:\n<em>Unchanged until after the db service</em>\n  redis:\n    image: redis:latest\n    restart: always\n    networks:\n      - external_network</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now when we next run <code>docker-compose up -d</code> we will see the Redis image and underlying layers being pulled and the container started.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our next stop is to install a WordPress caching plug-in. In the WordPress admin view, visit the \"Plugins\" page, and select \"Add new\". We are going to install two plugins - one to cache WordPress content for unauthenticated users, and another to enable us to connect to a Redis container.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, we will search for Redis and install and activate the official <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/redis-cache/\">Redis Object Cache</a> plugin. To enable our WordPress instance to connect to our Redis instance, we will also need to add two options manually to the end of our WordPress configuration file <code>wordpress/wp-config.php</code>, before the line saying \"That\'s all, stop editing!\" Because the user in the WordPress container does not match the <code>opc</code> userid, we will edit the file as root using <code>sudo</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>...\n// Redis configuration\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_HOST\', \'redis\');\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_PORT\', \'6379\');\n\n/* That\'s all, stop editing! Happy publishing. */\n...</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our Redis instance will now be used automatically as an object cache by WordPress. This means that when PHP objects are created in memory for things like users, posts, and pages, those objects will be stored in Redis in addition to being used to generate web pages for the user. The next time the same query is received, those objects will be loaded from Redis, rather than being created dynamically from a database query. As a result, we reduce both the load to the database, and the amount of PHP which needs to run to construct a page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we will install and activate the plugin <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/w3-total-cache/\">W3 Total Cache</a>, a page caching plugin. This plug-in will cache pages after they are created, and serve them to unauthenticated users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 19:45:13','2023-02-24 19:45:13','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=61',0,'revision','',0),(63,2,'2023-02-24 19:51:33','2023-02-24 19:51:33','','Redis_object_cache_working','','inherit','open','closed','','redis_object_cache_working','','','2023-02-24 19:51:33','2023-02-24 19:51:33','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Redis_object_cache_working.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(64,2,'2023-02-24 19:51:56','2023-02-24 19:51:56','','Add_Redis_plugin','','inherit','open','closed','','add_redis_plugin','','','2023-02-24 19:51:56','2023-02-24 19:51:56','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Add_Redis_plugin.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(65,2,'2023-02-24 19:56:38','2023-02-24 19:56:38','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. First, we will add a new <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/redis\">Redis service</a> to our Docker application in <code>docker-compose.yml</code>. The default container configuration will suffice for us, since our Redis instance will not be exposed outside of our container application:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>services:\n<em>Unchanged until after the db service</em>\n  redis:\n    image: redis:latest\n    restart: always\n    networks:\n      - external_network</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now when we next run <code>docker-compose up -d</code> we will see the Redis image and underlying layers being pulled and the container started.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our next stop is to install a WordPress caching plug-in. In the WordPress admin view, visit the \"Plugins\" page, and select \"Add new\". We are going to install two plugins - one to cache WordPress content for unauthenticated users, and another to enable us to connect to a Redis container.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":64,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Add_Redis_plugin-1024x558.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-64\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Searching for the Redis plugin</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, we will search for Redis and install and activate the official <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/redis-cache/\">Redis Object Cache</a> plugin. To enable our WordPress instance to connect to our Redis instance, we will also need to add two options manually to the end of our WordPress configuration file <code>wordpress/wp-config.php</code>, before the line saying \"That\'s all, stop editing!\" Because the user in the WordPress container does not match the <code>opc</code> userid, we will edit the file as root using <code>sudo</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>...\n// Redis configuration\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_HOST\', \'redis\');\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_PORT\', \'6379\');\n\n/* That\'s all, stop editing! Happy publishing. */\n...</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the Redis plugin options, we can now verify that the object cache is working by enabling the object cache, the connection will be verified. Our Redis instance will now be used automatically as an object cache by WordPress. This means that when PHP objects are created in memory for things like users, posts, and pages, those objects will be stored in Redis in addition to being used to generate web pages for the user. The next time the same query is received, those objects will be loaded from Redis, rather than being created dynamically from a database query. As a result, we reduce both the load to the database, and the amount of PHP which needs to run to construct a page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":63,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Redis_object_cache_working.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-63\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The connection is validated</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we will install and activate the plugin <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/w3-total-cache/\">W3 Total Cache</a>, a page caching plugin. This plug-in will cache pages after they are created, and serve them to unauthenticated users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 19:56:38','2023-02-24 19:56:38','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=65',0,'revision','',0),(67,2,'2023-02-24 20:06:09','2023-02-24 20:06:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. First, we will add a new <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/redis\">Redis service</a> to our Docker application in <code>docker-compose.yml</code>. The default container configuration will suffice for us, since our Redis instance will not be exposed outside of our container application:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>services:\n<em>Unchanged until after the db service</em>\n  redis:\n    image: redis:latest\n    restart: always\n    networks:\n      - external_network</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now when we next run <code>docker-compose up -d</code> we will see the Redis image and underlying layers being pulled and the container started.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our next stop is to install a WordPress caching plug-in. In the WordPress admin view, visit the \"Plugins\" page, and select \"Add new\". We are going to install two plugins - one to cache WordPress content for unauthenticated users, and another to enable us to connect to a Redis container.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":64,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Add_Redis_plugin-1024x558.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-64\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Searching for the Redis plugin</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, we will search for Redis and install and activate the official <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/redis-cache/\">Redis Object Cache</a> plugin. To enable our WordPress instance to connect to our Redis instance, we will also need to add two options manually to the end of our WordPress configuration file <code>wordpress/wp-config.php</code>, before the line saying \"That\'s all, stop editing!\" Because the user in the WordPress container does not match the <code>opc</code> userid, we will edit the file as root using <code>sudo</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>...\n// Redis configuration\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_HOST\', \'redis\');\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_PORT\', \'6379\');\n\n/* That\'s all, stop editing! Happy publishing. */\n...</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the Redis plugin options, we can now verify that the object cache is working by enabling the object cache, the connection will be verified. Our Redis instance will now be used automatically as an object cache by WordPress. This means that when PHP objects are created in memory for things like users, posts, and pages, those objects will be stored in Redis in addition to being used to generate web pages for the user. The next time the same query is received, those objects will be loaded from Redis, rather than being created dynamically from a database query. As a result, we reduce both the load to the database, and the amount of PHP which needs to run to construct a page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":63,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Redis_object_cache_working.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-63\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The connection is validated</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we will install and activate <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-super-cache/\">WP Super Cache</a>, a page caching plugin. This plug-in will cache pages after they are created, and serve them to unauthenticated users. The installation is a two-step process. First we search for, install, and activate the plugin in the plugins page</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 20:06:09','2023-02-24 20:06:09','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=67',0,'revision','',0),(68,2,'2023-02-24 20:09:18','2023-02-24 20:09:18','','activated_wp_supercache','','inherit','open','closed','','activated_wp_supercache','','','2023-02-24 20:09:18','2023-02-24 20:09:18','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/activated_wp_supercache.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(69,2,'2023-02-24 20:12:28','2023-02-24 20:12:28','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. First, we will add a new <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/redis\">Redis service</a> to our Docker application in <code>docker-compose.yml</code>. The default container configuration will suffice for us, since our Redis instance will not be exposed outside of our container application:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>services:\n<em>Unchanged until after the db service</em>\n  redis:\n    image: redis:latest\n    restart: always\n    networks:\n      - external_network</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now when we next run <code>docker-compose up -d</code> we will see the Redis image and underlying layers being pulled and the container started.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our next stop is to install a WordPress caching plug-in. In the WordPress admin view, visit the \"Plugins\" page, and select \"Add new\". We are going to install two plugins - one to cache WordPress content for unauthenticated users, and another to enable us to connect to a Redis container.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":64,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Add_Redis_plugin-1024x558.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-64\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Searching for the Redis plugin</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, we will search for Redis and install and activate the official <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/redis-cache/\">Redis Object Cache</a> plugin. To enable our WordPress instance to connect to our Redis instance, we will also need to add two options manually to the end of our WordPress configuration file <code>wordpress/wp-config.php</code>, before the line saying \"That\'s all, stop editing!\" Because the user in the WordPress container does not match the <code>opc</code> userid, we will edit the file as root using <code>sudo</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>...\n// Redis configuration\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_HOST\', \'redis\');\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_PORT\', \'6379\');\n\n/* That\'s all, stop editing! Happy publishing. */\n...</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the Redis plugin options, we can now verify that the object cache is working by enabling the object cache, the connection will be verified. Our Redis instance will now be used automatically as an object cache by WordPress. This means that when PHP objects are created in memory for things like users, posts, and pages, those objects will be stored in Redis in addition to being used to generate web pages for the user. The next time the same query is received, those objects will be loaded from Redis, rather than being created dynamically from a database query. As a result, we reduce both the load to the database, and the amount of PHP which needs to run to construct a page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":63,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Redis_object_cache_working.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-63\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The connection is validated</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we will install and activate <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-super-cache/\">WP Super Cache</a>, a page caching plugin. This plug-in will cache pages after they are created, and serve them to unauthenticated users. The installation is a two-step process. First we search for and install the plugin in the plugins page, then we need to activate the plugin in its settings page. After enabling page caching, we can test the caching on the settings page to verify that it is working.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":68,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/activated_wp_supercache-1024x536.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-68\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The WP SuperCache settings page after the plugin is activated</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The plug-in will provide a number of other useful resources for improving the performance of your page, but those are outside the scope of this tutorial.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We now have a multi-container application load-balancing calls across three WordPress instances, caching pages that can be served statically to improve performance, and caching PHP objects to reduce load on both our web servers and our database, all masked behind a proxy nginx service. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 20:12:28','2023-02-24 20:12:28','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=69',0,'revision','',0),(70,2,'2023-02-24 20:19:12','2023-02-24 20:19:12','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now turn our attention to various methods of caching that we can enable for our WordPress installation. First, we will add a new <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/redis\">Redis service</a> to our Docker application in <code>docker-compose.yml</code>. The default container configuration will suffice for us, since our Redis instance will not be exposed outside of our container application:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>services:\n<em>Unchanged until after the db service</em>\n  redis:\n    image: redis:latest\n    restart: always\n    networks:\n      - external_network</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now when we next run <code>docker-compose up -d</code> we will see the Redis image and underlying layers being pulled and the container started.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our next stop is to install a WordPress caching plug-in. In the WordPress admin view, visit the \"Plugins\" page, and select \"Add new\". We are going to install two plugins - one to cache WordPress content for unauthenticated users, and another to enable us to connect to a Redis container.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":64,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Add_Redis_plugin-1024x558.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-64\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Searching for the Redis plugin</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, we will search for Redis and install and activate the official <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/redis-cache/\">Redis Object Cache</a> plugin. To enable our WordPress instance to connect to our Redis instance, we will also need to add two options manually to the end of our WordPress configuration file <code>wordpress/wp-config.php</code>, before the line saying \"That\'s all, stop editing!\" Because the user in the WordPress container does not match the <code>opc</code> userid, we will edit the file as root using <code>sudo</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>...\n// Redis configuration\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_HOST\', \'redis\');\ndefine(\'WP_REDIS_PORT\', \'6379\');\n\n/* That\'s all, stop editing! Happy publishing. */\n...</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the Redis plugin options, we can now verify that the object cache is working by enabling the object cache, the connection will be verified. Our Redis instance will now be used automatically as an object cache by WordPress. This means that when PHP objects are created in memory for things like users, posts, and pages, those objects will be stored in Redis in addition to being used to generate web pages for the user. The next time the same query is received, those objects will be loaded from Redis, rather than being created dynamically from a database query. As a result, we reduce both the load to the database, and the amount of PHP which needs to run to construct a page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":63,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Redis_object_cache_working.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-63\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The connection is validated</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we will install and activate <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-super-cache/\">WP Super Cache</a>, a page caching plugin. This plug-in will cache pages after they are created, and serve them to unauthenticated users. The installation is a two-step process. First we search for and install the plugin in the plugins page, then we need to activate the plugin in its settings page. After enabling page caching, we can test the caching on the settings page to verify that it is working.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":68,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/activated_wp_supercache-1024x536.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-68\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The WP SuperCache settings page after the plugin is activated</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The plug-in will provide a number of other useful resources for improving the performance of your page, but those are outside the scope of this tutorial.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We now have a multi-container application load-balancing calls across three WordPress instances, caching pages that can be served statically to improve performance, and caching PHP objects to reduce load on both our web servers and our database, all masked behind a proxy nginx service. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As I wrote at the beginning, there are many more steps possible to create a production service:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Enable secure HTTPS connections by generating and using SSL certificates</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Regularly backing up our database, and verifying emergency restoration</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Creating a custom container image with our plugins pre-installed to make automated deployment and upgrades easier</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Introducing monitoring to measure performance and receive alerts when the performance drops</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Moving to Kubernetes for a distributed, clustered application that can take advantage of cloud resources</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Using an object store for static resources added to the WordPress instance like uploaded images</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Concealing passwords with Kubernetes secrets</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Scaling our database, if that becomes necessary, with read-only replicas or sharding</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But already in a very short time, we can now connect multiple Docker containers together, scale our application using load balancing, and accelerate the performance for end-users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 4: Enabling caching','','inherit','closed','closed','','45-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 20:19:12','2023-02-24 20:19:12','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=70',0,'revision','',0),(71,2,'2023-02-24 20:22:57','2023-02-24 20:22:57','','Add_Redis_plugin','','inherit','open','closed','','add_redis_plugin-2','','','2023-02-24 20:22:57','2023-02-24 20:22:57','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Add_Redis_plugin.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(72,2,'2023-02-24 20:23:02','2023-02-24 20:23:02','','Redis_object_cache_working','','inherit','open','closed','','redis_object_cache_working-2','','','2023-02-24 20:23:02','2023-02-24 20:23:02','',45,'http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Redis_object_cache_working.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(73,2,'2023-02-24 20:26:20','2023-02-24 20:26:20','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is an example page. It\'s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>Hi there! I\'m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin\' caught in the rain.)</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>...or something like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-admin/\">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Sample Page','','inherit','closed','closed','','2-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 20:26:20','2023-02-24 20:26:20','',2,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=73',0,'revision','',0),(74,2,'2023-02-24 20:26:32','2023-02-24 20:26:32','<!-- wp:heading --><h2>Who we are</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Our website address is: http://129.213.187.155.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Comments</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor&#8217;s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Media</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Cookies</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select &quot;Remember Me&quot;, your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Embedded content from other websites</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Who we share your data with</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you request a password reset, your IP address will be included in the reset email.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>How long we retain your data</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>What rights you have over your data</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Where your data is sent</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Privacy Policy','','inherit','closed','closed','','3-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 20:26:32','2023-02-24 20:26:32','',3,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=74',0,'revision','',0),(75,2,'2023-02-24 20:49:42','2023-02-24 20:49:42','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before starting this tutorial, you will need an Ampere Altra A1 instance running on Oracle Cloud.  Throughout this session, we will assume that you are running Oracle Linux 8, and the tutorial has made this assumption for all commands, file locations, and usernames.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create an instance, first sign up to <a href=\"https://cloud.oracle.com\">Oracle Cloud</a>, and on the dashboard select \"Create a VM instance\" in the \"Launch Resources\" section. We will create the instance in the \"root\" compartment. In the \"Image and shape\" section, we are going to edit the defaults, and under \"Shape\", we will change the shape to choose the Ampere type, with 4 OCPUs and 12 GB of RAM - this will max out your \"Always Free\" quota.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you already have a workload running, you can certainly complete this tutorial with a smaller instance, but you will increase resource contention as we increase the number of containers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:image {\"id\":76,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Oracle_Cloud_Shape_family-1024x503.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-76\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Choosing the Ampere shape series</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":78,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/OCI_shape_sizing-1-1024x431.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-78\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Sizing the instance</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will also need to movify the Virtual Cloud Network settings for the instance to enable HTTP and HTTPS traffic and get a public IPv4 address. Then generate an SSH key pair (or upload the public key to one you already have) to allow you to connect to the instance over SSH.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have completed these settings, you can click \"Create\" to start your instance. When you click on your instance name, you can  find its public IP address for connections.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also automate the creation of instances using a tool like Terraform - there are <a href=\"https://github.com/amperecomputing/terraform-oci-ampere-a1\">tutorials available</a> to help you on Ampere\'s github page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Getting Started with Ampere A1 on Oracle Cloud','','publish','closed','closed','','getting-started-with-ampere-a1-on-oracle-cloud','','','2023-02-24 20:49:42','2023-02-24 20:49:42','',0,'http://129.213.187.155/?page_id=75',0,'page','',0),(76,2,'2023-02-24 20:40:58','2023-02-24 20:40:58','','Oracle_Cloud_Shape_family','','inherit','open','closed','','oracle_cloud_shape_family','','','2023-02-24 20:40:58','2023-02-24 20:40:58','',75,'http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Oracle_Cloud_Shape_family.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(77,2,'2023-02-24 20:41:50','2023-02-24 20:41:50','','OCI_shape_sizing','','inherit','open','closed','','oci_shape_sizing','','','2023-02-24 20:41:50','2023-02-24 20:41:50','',75,'http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/OCI_shape_sizing.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(78,2,'2023-02-24 20:42:46','2023-02-24 20:42:46','','OCI_shape_sizing-1','','inherit','open','closed','','oci_shape_sizing-1','','','2023-02-24 20:42:46','2023-02-24 20:42:46','',75,'http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/OCI_shape_sizing-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(79,2,'2023-02-24 20:49:42','2023-02-24 20:49:42','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before starting this tutorial, you will need an Ampere Altra A1 instance running on Oracle Cloud.  Throughout this session, we will assume that you are running Oracle Linux 8, and the tutorial has made this assumption for all commands, file locations, and usernames.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create an instance, first sign up to <a href=\"https://cloud.oracle.com\">Oracle Cloud</a>, and on the dashboard select \"Create a VM instance\" in the \"Launch Resources\" section. We will create the instance in the \"root\" compartment. In the \"Image and shape\" section, we are going to edit the defaults, and under \"Shape\", we will change the shape to choose the Ampere type, with 4 OCPUs and 12 GB of RAM - this will max out your \"Always Free\" quota.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you already have a workload running, you can certainly complete this tutorial with a smaller instance, but you will increase resource contention as we increase the number of containers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:image {\"id\":76,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Oracle_Cloud_Shape_family-1024x503.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-76\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Choosing the Ampere shape series</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":78,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/OCI_shape_sizing-1-1024x431.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-78\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Sizing the instance</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will also need to movify the Virtual Cloud Network settings for the instance to enable HTTP and HTTPS traffic and get a public IPv4 address. Then generate an SSH key pair (or upload the public key to one you already have) to allow you to connect to the instance over SSH.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have completed these settings, you can click \"Create\" to start your instance. When you click on your instance name, you can  find its public IP address for connections.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also automate the creation of instances using a tool like Terraform - there are <a href=\"https://github.com/amperecomputing/terraform-oci-ampere-a1\">tutorials available</a> to help you on Ampere\'s github page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Getting Started with Ampere A1 on Oracle Cloud','','inherit','closed','closed','','75-revision-v1','','','2023-02-24 20:49:42','2023-02-24 20:49:42','',75,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=79',0,'revision','',0),(80,2,'2023-02-28 19:58:17','2023-02-28 19:58:17','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This hour, we will take a journey through what is involved in putting together a realistic cloud-native application using Docker containers in a single Ampere A1 VM instance on Oracle Cloud. By the end of our time together, you will have:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Created a Wordpress instance and a separate MySQL instance with some reference content</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Added an nginx proxy to enable us to hid the application\'s internal architecture, and make changes to scale our application</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Enable load balancing across multiple WordPress instances</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Installed a caching system which will serve static content more efficiently</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Added a Redis object cache which will reduce the amount of compute power used by our web servers</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>At least step, we will test the performance of our instance to verify that we are improving its performance and scalability</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For the purposes of today\'s presentation, we will do all of these in a single 4 OCPU Ampere Altra A1 instance on the OCI Always Free tier. There are lots of things we could do to continue to make this application more \"cloud native\", including registering for SSL certificates and enabling secure access over HTTPS, using object storage for uploads rather than saving them to the filesystem, backing up our database for effective disaster recovery, adding monitoring to ensure that we stay on top of the load of the application, and moving our application to a clustered solution based on Kubernetes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, all of this is out of scope for today. By the end of today\'s session, you will have a total of six container instances running. We will map port 80 of our VM to port 80 of the nginx container, and use a network bridge to connect all of our application containers. Our final WordPress architecture will look like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://129.213.187.155/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Application_diagram-1024x576.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Application architecture for today</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Prerequisites</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have your instance running Oracle Linux, there are a few things we will need to install to ensure that we can run <code>docker-compose</code> to launch our application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>As root, installing Docker, and updating operating system packages:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>sudo -s</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>dnf install -y yum-utils</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>yum-config-manager --add-repo https://download.docker.com/linux/centos/docker-ce.repo</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>dnf update -y &amp;&amp; dnf install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Enabling Docker, and ensuring that the <code>opc</code> user can run it:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>systemctl start docker &amp;&amp; systemctl enable docker</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>usermod -aG docker opc</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>sudo -s -u opc</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Now check that the <code>opc</code> user is in the <code>docker</code> group:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>groups</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>docker run hello-world</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Download and install <code>docker-compose</code>:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Check <code>https://github.com/docker/compose/releases</code> for more recent releases. Make sure we choose the <code>linux-aarch64</code> binary</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>sudo curl -L https://github.com/docker/compose/releases/download/v2.16.0/docker-compose-linux-aarch64 -o /usr/local/bin/docker-compose &amp;&amp; sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/docker-compose</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Finally, we will install <code>git</code> and download the repository for today\'s session:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>sudo dnf install -y git</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>git clone https://github.com/AmpereComputing/pi-day-tutorial</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We now have everything we need to get started! We will build up in stages. In stage 1, we will start a new WordPress instance from scratch, and go through the installation process. In stage 2, we will pre-load some content (including this post and documentation for this session!) to our WordPress instance, and add an <code>nginx</code> proxy to pass through connections. In stage 3, we will start another two WordPress instances and configure <code>nginx</code> to load balance across them. Finally, in stage 4, we will add a caching plug-in to WordPress, start a Redis instance, and configure WordPress to use Redis as an object cache.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://129.213.187.155/2023/02/24/a-basic-wordpress-installation/\" data-type=\"post\" data-id=\"10\">Let\'s get started!</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Welcome to Pi Day 2023','','inherit','closed','closed','','7-revision-v1','','','2023-02-28 19:58:17','2023-02-28 19:58:17','',7,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=80',0,'revision','',0),(81,2,'2023-02-28 20:03:03','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2023-02-28 20:03:03','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=81',0,'post','',0),(82,2,'2023-02-28 20:21:38','2023-02-28 20:21:38','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now we will enable ourselves to evolve the application architecture by separating out the HTTP end-point that users connect to from the application server that is serving content. To do this, we will use <code>nginx</code> as a fast, lightweight proxy, and continue to use an Apache2/php instance running WordPress to generate the dynamic content. For the moment, wer should not see a big change in performance, but this is an important step to enabling us to scale our application by caching content, and load-balancing compute-heavy work across multiple instances.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The main change we will make in <code>docker-compose.yml</code> is to add a new <code>proxy</code> service which will download the latest <code>nginx</code> container, pass through host port 80 to the container (we remove this config from our <code>wordpress</code> container).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>version: \"3\"\n\nservices:\n  proxy:\n    restart: always\n    image: nginx:latest\n    networks: \n      - external_network\n    ports:\n      - 80:80\n    volumes:\n      - ./nginx/tmp:/var/run/nginx\n      - ./nginx/conf.d:/etc/nginx/conf.d\n    command: &#91; nginx-debug, \'-g\', \'daemon off;\' ]\n<em>everything else is unchanged</em></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We now map a custom configuration for our WordPress install into the <code>/etc/nginx/conf.d</code> directory of our container. This basic nginx configuration specifies that we are the default server for all connections to port 80, regardless of the requested domain name (this allows us to connect using just the IP address), and that all requests should be passed to the <code>wordpress</code> service:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>server {\n        listen 80 default_server;\n        listen   &#91;::]:80 default_server;\n\n        server_name example.com;\n        location / {\n            proxy_pass http://wordpress;\n        }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We also added a new database file to <code>mysql/initdb</code> which maps to the special directory in the container <code>/docker-entrypoint-initdb.d</code> - if the database is not already initialized, the database back-up in this directory will automatically be loaded at start-up, as described in <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/mysql\">the DockerHub page for MySQL</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we start the application with a database dump, it takes a few seconds for the database to become available. We can force the <code>wordpress</code> container to wait for the database to be ready by adding a <code>depends_on</code> condition to the WordPress container options.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before starting our application, you will need to update two IP addresses used by WordPress as part of its configuration. In <code>mysql/initdb/pi_day.sql</code>, search for the IP address <code>129.213.187.155</code> (the IP address obtained by me while preparing this tutorial) and replace it for the settings <code>siteurl</code> and <code>home</code> with the IP address for your instance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After running <code>docker-compose up -d</code> with this file, we now have 3 containers running, and the service should take about 20 seconds to start up, because WordPress now waits for the database to become available after loading our saved database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;opc@cloud-native-wordpress wordpress2]$ docker-compose up -d\n&#91;+] Running 4/4\n  Network wordpress2_external_network  Created                                                                  0.3s\n  Container wordpress2-db-1            Healthy                                                                 21.0s\n  Container wordpress2-proxy-1         Started                                                                  0.6s\n  Container wordpress2-wordpress-1     Started                                                                 21.3s\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now see how queries are being handled by the server by checking the logs with <code>docker-compose logs -f</code> (the <code>-f</code> option allows us to follow along in real-time) while we interact with the website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we send a request to the site, we first see that the message is intercepted by <code>wordpress2-proxy-1</code> before being passed along to <code>wordpress2-wordpress-1</code>, where the page request is satisfied and returned to the requester.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>wordpress2-wordpress-1  | 172.20.0.4 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:01 +0000] \"GET / HTTP/1.0\" 200 11352 \"-\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\"\nwordpress2-proxy-1      | 173.76.40.122 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:01 +0000] \"GET / HTTP/1.1\" 200 10949 \"-\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\" \"-\"\nwordpress2-proxy-1      | 173.76.40.122 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:02 +0000] \"GET /2023/02/24/welcome-to-pi-day-2023/ HTTP/1.1\" 200 14761 \"http://129.213.187.155/\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\" \"-\"\nwordpress2-wordpress-1  | 172.20.0.4 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:02 +0000] \"GET /2023/02/24/welcome-to-pi-day-2023/ HTTP/1.0\" 200 15359 \"http://129.213.187.155/\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\"</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before proceeding: a word on creating database back-ups. To run commands in the context of the container, we can use <code>docker-compose exec servicename &lt;cmd&gt;</code>. To generate database back-ups for our WordPress instance, we run <code>mysqldump</code> inside the container as the database root user - giving the database root password we passed to the container at startup when prompter - and save the SQL file generated to the local filesystem, with:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>docker-compose exec db mysqldump -u root -p wordpress &gt; pi_day.sql</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When running a live service, you will want to do this every day in a cron job, and save several days of back-ups, to ensure that you can restore the service quickly in the event of unexpected data loss.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can now connect to this WordPress instance with the username <code>piday</code>, password <code>3.141592</code> - and don\'t worry abou</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that we have a proxy, and the ability to reload our database after completely changing the application architecture, we are ready to experiment with load balancing! <a href=\"http://129.213.187.155/2023/02/24/using-nginx-as-a-load-balancer/\" data-type=\"post\" data-id=\"28\">Let\'s move on to part 3</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 2: Adding a proxy','','inherit','closed','closed','','13-autosave-v1','','','2023-02-28 20:21:38','2023-02-28 20:21:38','',13,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=82',0,'revision','',0),(83,2,'2023-02-28 20:22:35','2023-02-28 20:22:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now we will enable ourselves to evolve the application architecture by separating out the HTTP end-point that users connect to from the application server that is serving content. To do this, we will use <code>nginx</code> as a fast, lightweight proxy, and continue to use an Apache2/php instance running WordPress to generate the dynamic content. For the moment, wer should not see a big change in performance, but this is an important step to enabling us to scale our application by caching content, and load-balancing compute-heavy work across multiple instances.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The main change we will make in <code>docker-compose.yml</code> is to add a new <code>proxy</code> service which will download the latest <code>nginx</code> container, pass through host port 80 to the container (we remove this config from our <code>wordpress</code> container).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>version: \"3\"\n\nservices:\n  proxy:\n    restart: always\n    image: nginx:latest\n    networks: \n      - external_network\n    ports:\n      - 80:80\n    volumes:\n      - ./nginx/tmp:/var/run/nginx\n      - ./nginx/conf.d:/etc/nginx/conf.d\n    command: &#91; nginx-debug, \'-g\', \'daemon off;\' ]\n<em>everything else is unchanged</em></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We now map a custom configuration for our WordPress install into the <code>/etc/nginx/conf.d</code> directory of our container. This basic nginx configuration specifies that we are the default server for all connections to port 80, regardless of the requested domain name (this allows us to connect using just the IP address), and that all requests should be passed to the <code>wordpress</code> service:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>server {\n        listen 80 default_server;\n        listen   &#91;::]:80 default_server;\n\n        server_name example.com;\n        location / {\n            proxy_pass http://wordpress;\n        }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We also added a new database file to <code>mysql/initdb</code> which maps to the special directory in the container <code>/docker-entrypoint-initdb.d</code> - if the database is not already initialized, the database back-up in this directory will automatically be loaded at start-up, as described in <a href=\"https://hub.docker.com/_/mysql\">the DockerHub page for MySQL</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we start the application with a database dump, it takes a few seconds for the database to become available. We can force the <code>wordpress</code> container to wait for the database to be ready by adding a <code>depends_on</code> condition to the WordPress container options.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before starting our application, you will need to update two IP addresses used by WordPress as part of its configuration. In <code>mysql/initdb/pi_day.sql</code>, search for the IP address <code>129.213.187.155</code> (the IP address obtained by me while preparing this tutorial) and replace it for the settings <code>siteurl</code> and <code>home</code> with the IP address for your instance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After running <code>docker-compose up -d</code> with this file, we now have 3 containers running, and the service should take about 20 seconds to start up, because WordPress now waits for the database to become available after loading our saved database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;opc@cloud-native-wordpress wordpress2]$ docker-compose up -d\n&#91;+] Running 4/4\n  Network wordpress2_external_network  Created                                                                  0.3s\n  Container wordpress2-db-1            Healthy                                                                 21.0s\n  Container wordpress2-proxy-1         Started                                                                  0.6s\n  Container wordpress2-wordpress-1     Started                                                                 21.3s\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We can now see how queries are being handled by the server by checking the logs with <code>docker-compose logs -f</code> (the <code>-f</code> option allows us to follow along in real-time) while we interact with the website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we send a request to the site, we first see that the message is intercepted by <code>wordpress2-proxy-1</code> before being passed along to <code>wordpress2-wordpress-1</code>, where the page request is satisfied and returned to the requester.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>wordpress2-wordpress-1  | 172.20.0.4 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:01 +0000] \"GET / HTTP/1.0\" 200 11352 \"-\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\"\nwordpress2-proxy-1      | 173.76.40.122 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:01 +0000] \"GET / HTTP/1.1\" 200 10949 \"-\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\" \"-\"\nwordpress2-proxy-1      | 173.76.40.122 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:02 +0000] \"GET /2023/02/24/welcome-to-pi-day-2023/ HTTP/1.1\" 200 14761 \"http://129.213.187.155/\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\" \"-\"\nwordpress2-wordpress-1  | 172.20.0.4 - - &#91;24/Feb/2023:01:52:02 +0000] \"GET /2023/02/24/welcome-to-pi-day-2023/ HTTP/1.0\" 200 15359 \"http://129.213.187.155/\" \"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/110.0.0.0 Safari/537.36\"</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before proceeding: a word on creating database back-ups. To run commands in the context of the container, we can use <code>docker-compose exec servicename &lt;cmd&gt;</code>. To generate database back-ups for our WordPress instance, we run <code>mysqldump</code> inside the container as the database root user - giving the database root password we passed to the container at startup when prompter - and save the SQL file generated to the local filesystem, with:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>docker-compose exec db mysqldump -u root -p wordpress &gt; pi_day.sql</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When running a live service, you will want to do this every day in a cron job, and save several days of back-ups, to ensure that you can restore the service quickly in the event of unexpected data loss.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can now connect to this WordPress instance with the username <code>piday</code>, password <code>3.141592</code> - and don\'t worry about messing things up, we can always stop our containers, wipe out the database, and return to this point again by rerunning <code>docker-compose up -d</code>!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that we have a proxy, and the ability to reload our database after completely changing the application architecture, we are ready to experiment with load balancing! <a href=\"http://129.213.187.155/2023/02/24/using-nginx-as-a-load-balancer/\" data-type=\"post\" data-id=\"28\">Let\'s move on to part 3</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Part 2: Adding a proxy','','inherit','closed','closed','','13-revision-v1','','','2023-02-28 20:22:35','2023-02-28 20:22:35','',13,'http://129.213.187.155/?p=83',0,'revision','',0);
